caption:
Variola Virus | Plaguing millions of individuals in the 20th Century, the variola virus or commonly known as Smallpox, was eradicated by 1980. .
All remaining samples of the virus were recommended by the WHO to be destroyed or sent to containment facilities. However, the threats of use as a biological weapon still exist today. .
The variola virus has a single linear double stranded DNA. While the variola virus only affects humans, there are 3 other orthopoxviruses (genus) that can infect humans: vaccinia, cowpox, and monkeypox. .
Smallpox was eradicated through a combination of surveillance and identificstion of new cases, and a method refered to as 'ring vaccination'. This meant any individual suspected to have contracted the virus was found and treated as soon as possible, this preventing it's spread. .
I highly recommend a documentary by @historychannelcanada called 'The Deadly Smallpox Virus'.

caption:
Welcome to Microbiology Mondays🤗! The first of two weekly posts I'm launching this month.
-
Let's talk about antibiotics💊! You may have encountered these (or been fortunate enough not to need them! Antibiotics are small molecules that either prevent the growth of⏳, or directly kill☠️, bacteria. What you may not know about them is that the majority of antibiotics in circulation are derived from organisms in complex microbial communities, such as soil, and natural resistance to these is common!
-
So...why does that matter to us? Since the advent of penicillin in 1942, there have only been a handful of new antibiotics discovered to date, and with almost every antibiotic we have there has been a human case🤕 example of infections with a bacteria that is resistant to one (or all of them disturbingly😵). We are quickly entering the "post-antibiotic era"...which is almost more disturbing that climate change🤯.
-
Enter Teixobactin👨🏼‍🔬! This is a really exciting new antibiotic, also isolated from a bacteria that resides in soil. What's exciting about this is that it is a highly unusual molecule with no detectable reistance!. It affects what is known as "Gram positive" bacteria, examples of which you may know💭 as golden staph and tuberculosis. Teixobactin is produced much like any other gene (as a protein!🍗), so it is very possible to manipulate the gene to increase its effect! Such improvements in structure have shown extremely promising results in mouse models of infection, making it one of the most potent antibiotics known for Gram positive bacteria.
-
Why does this matter? It is imperative that we keep finding 🕵️ new ones, quickly testing them🔬, making them better💪 and, importantly, making sure they are safe for use in humans👨‍👩‍👦‍👦! Without these kinds of discoveries we could very quickly enter a period where even a minor infection could be life threatening as we would have no drugs with which to treat it😱!
-
Have you encountered a "resistant" infection before? What do you think about the use of genetic modification to enhance the effectiveness of antibiotics? Let me know in the comments below👇!

caption:
Newborn antibiotic ointment is used primarily to fight eye infections and prevent blindness associated with the transmission of gonorrhea and chlamydia.  If the birthing mother does not carry these sexually transmitted infections, the ointment is completely unnecessary.  Typically, women are screened at least twice during pregnancy for gonorrhea and/or chlamydiaand undergo treatment, if necessary.  Most states governed in the U.S. mandate that newborns undergo prophylaxis treatment via application of the ointment, regardless of the mother’s status or birthing method (vaginal or cesarean). Research this routine newborn intervention!! You CAN exercise your right to informed refusal and here are a few reasons why you should:

1.  It may be unnecessary for YOUR baby given the  situation;
2. Erythromycin ointment is an antibiotic that can still harm your baby’s natural gut flora;
3. It can cause eye irritation and blurred vision which interferes with bonding and the establishment of breastfeeding. 🤱🏻 Doctors take an oath to first do no harm.  This medication may seem harmless but it’s not.  In fact, the label itself says to keep out of the reach of children.  Ironically, that’s who it is administered to most frequently! If the medical and pharmaceutical professions recommend something for your baby that is completely unwarranted, what else are they recommending that might be unnecessary or perhaps even harmful? 🤔🤨🧐 If you plan to birth in a hospital, check your state laws and make sure you aren’t living in a police state (like New York). Some hospitals decline the parental right to informed refusal and will call CPS and have the baby removed temporarily from your custody so the ointment can be administered.  Talk to your doctor.  Note your desire to refuse in your birth plan if this is something you wish to decline.  If you can’t decline because the law does not permit you the liberty to do so, ask for administration to be delayed by several hours so you have a chance to bond before the baby’s vision is blurred for no dang good reason.

#evidencebasedbirthing
#informedparenting

#PROVAX #REBUTTAL  Q: So you're an #antivaxxer now?
A: Yes. 
Q: Don't you worry about your child getting #sick from #vaccine preventable #diseases?
A: No, not really. I actually have less #fear of many of those illnesses now that I've done my #research. 
Q: But what about #polio?
A: Wild #Polio is #asymptomatic in over 90% of cases. When symptoms do present, they're usually mild and flu-like. They only reason it was #paralytic after the turn of the century was the combination of polio virus and #Pesticide use (namely DDT). Q: But we don't see iron lungs anymore because of vaccines. 
A: We don't see iron lungs anymore for the same reason we don't see computers that are large enough to take up an entire room. Technology has come a long way.

Q: But even if the risk of getting something serious is small, don't you want to protect your #child with vaccines just in case?
A: I do want to protect my child, and that is one reason I say no to vaccines. Because in my #Benefit vs. #Risk analysis, the chances of my child being #harmed from vaccines is greater than the chances of my child being harmed from one of those illnesses. 
Q: But it's not just about your child. It is your responsibility to #vaccinate your child to #protect #immune compromised people through #herd #immunity.

caption:
Trends vs Science 🧪...........
Should you vaccinate? Give antibiotics?
••••••••••••••••••
Even though nutrition is my lane, I get just as many questions from mommas/moms-to-be about my thoughts on vaccinations and meds. In my home, I make decisions based on what is best/necessary for my daughter. She entered the world on antibiotics and is on them now with an ear infection. She is also on probiotics. She has also received all vaccinations to-date with no side effects. Our daycare, which is the top rated in our city, requires vaccinations. Here are common questions and research supported answers:
1). Do vaccines cause autism?
A: No. Nearly a dozen studies following millions of children conducted worldwide over the last decade have failed to find a connection between autism and childhood vaccines. The original, singular study that claimed to find a connection has been officially retracted by the publication and the author, Dr. Andrew Wakefield, lost his medical license when it was found that he lied.
2). Why do vaccinations start so young?
A: Babies are most vulnerable to serious, life-threatening diseases because their immune systems are still developing.
3). How can I trust that vaccines are safe?
A: Vaccines are one of the most thoroughly tested medical products available in the U.S. Before a vaccine can be considered for approval by the FDA, a vaccine manufacturer must show it is safe and effective through clinical trials.
4). But the ingredients can harm babies right?
A: No. It only takes a few misinformed people with a platform to spread info like this, that only promotes fear. The main ingredients in vaccines are antigens, which are small amounts of the bacteria or virus the person is being vaccinated against. Antigens are the parts of the vaccine that encourage your immune system to create antibodies to fight against future infections. Simply put, they build immunity against diseases. 
Of course, I always encourage people to make decisions that are right for themselves and their families. I’m just here to provide current research to help you make informed decisions.
••••••••••
